translator    =\n| image         = File:StoneOfDestiny.jpg\n| caption = First edition\n| author        = [[Ion Idriess]]\n| illustrator   =\n| cover_artist  =\n| country       = Australia\n| language      = English\n| series        =\n| genre         = non-fiction\n| publisher     = [[Angus and Robertson]]\n| release_date  = 1948\n| english_release_date =\n| media_type    =\n| pages         =\n| isbn          =\n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   =\n}}\n'''''Stone of Destiny''''' is a 1948 book by [[Ion Idriess]] about the Australian [[diamond]] industry.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article131352781 |title=BOOK REVIEW |newspaper=[[The Dubbo Liberal And Macquarie Advocate]] |volume=39 |issue=147 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=4 January 1949 |accessdate=16 April 2016 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>Kevin Fahy, 'Joris, Joannes Julius Alphonsus (1888\u20131963)', Australian Dictionary of Biography, National Centre of Biography, Australian National University, http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/joris-joannes-julius-alphonsus-10645/text18921, published first in hardcopy 1996, accessed online 18 April 2016.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/C498037 ''Stone of Destiny''] at [[AustLit]]\n{{Ion Idriess}}\n\n[[Category:1948 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Australian non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books by Ion Idriess]]\n[[Category:Diamond mining]]\n[[Category:Mining in Western Australia]]\n\n\n{{Australia-book-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "miscapitalization (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stone_of_Destiny_(book)"}
{"title_page": "Edward Master", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n'''Sir Edward Master(s)''' (2 August 1610 \u2013 22 January 1691) of Canterbury, Kent was an English politician who sat in the [[House of Commons of England|House of Commons]] at various times between 1640 and 1679.\n\nHe was the son of Giles Master of Henshurst, Woodchurch, Kent.<ref name=HoP>{{cite web|url=https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1660-1690/member/master-sir-edward-1610-91|title=MASTER, Sir Edward (1610-91), of Canterbury, Kent.|publisher=History of Parliament Trust|accessdate= 25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nMaster(s) was [[High Sheriff of Kent]] for 1639\u201340.<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=53762 ''General history: Sheriffs of Kent'', The History and Topographical Survey of the County of Kent: Volume 1 (1797), pp. 177-213. Date accessed: 17 November 2010]</ref>\n\nIn April 1640, he was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Canterbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Canterbury]] for the [[Short Parliament]]. In November 1640, he was re-elected MP for Canterbury in the [[Long Parliament]] and remained until 1653, surviving [[Pride's Purge]].<ref>{{Cite Notitia Parliamentaria|converted=1|part=2|pages=229\u2013239}}</ref> He was elected MP for Canterbury in 1661 and sat until 1679 in the [[Cavalier Parliament]].<ref>{{Rayment-hc|c|2|date=March 2012}}</ref> He was knighted in 1660.\n\nMaster(s) died aged 80 and was buried with a memorial at St Paul's Church, Canterbury.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jy0tAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA275&lpg=PA275&dq=%22Sir+Edward+Master%22+Canterbury&source=bl&ots=SLhbO8LZud&sig=uvQ9kYhFDLX_MiHgjnhuTNZHNkA&hl=en&ei=iBjkTIe3GYeDhQfTlcXODg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CEEQ6AEwBzgU#v=onepage&q=%22Sir%20Edward%20Master%22%20Canterbury&f=false Edward Hasted ''The History and topographical survey of the county of Kent, Volume 11'']</ref> He had married in 1635, Dorcas, the daughter of Sir [[Hugh Hamersley]], Lord Mayor of London 1627\u20138, and had many children, including at least 4 sons.<ref name=HoP/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|en}}\n{{succession box \n| title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Canterbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Canterbury]] \n| before= ''Parliament suspended since 1629''\n| with= [[John Nutt (MP)|John Nutt]]\n| years=1640\u20131653\n| after= ''Not represented in Barebones parliament''\n}}\n{{succession box\n|before=[[Anthony Aucher]]\n| before2=[[Heneage Finch, 1st Earl of Nottingham|Heneage Finch]]\n|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Canterbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Canterbury]]\n|with=[[Francis Lovelace (MP)|Francis Lovelace]] (1661\u20131664)\n|with2=[[Thomas Hardres]] (1664\u20131679)\n|years=1661\u20131679\n|after=[[Sir Edward Hales, 3rd Baronet|Edward Hales]]\n| after2=[[William Jacob (Canterbury MP)|William Jacob]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Master, Edward}}\n[[Category:1610 births]]\n[[Category:1691 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kent]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Kent]]\n[[Category:Politics of Canterbury]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1640 (April)]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1640\u20131648]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1648\u20131653]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1661\u20131679]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n\n\n{{England-pre1707-MP-stub}}\n{{England-mayor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n'''Sir Edward Master(s)''' (2 August 1610 \u2013 22 January 1691) of Canterbury, Kent was an English politician who sat in the [[House of Commons of England|House of Commons]] at various times between 1640 and 1679.\n\nHe was the son of Giles Master of Henshurst, Woodchurch, Kent.<ref name=HoP>{{cite web|url=https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1660-1690/member/master-sir-edward-1610-91|title=MASTER, Sir Edward (1610-91), of Canterbury, Kent.|publisher=History of Parliament Trust|accessdate= 25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nMaster(s) was [[High Sheriff of Kent]] for 1639\u201340.<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=53762 ''General history: Sheriffs of Kent'', The History and Topographical Survey of the County of Kent: Volume 1 (1797), pp. 177-213. Date accessed: 17 November 2010]</ref>\n\nIn April 1640, he was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Canterbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Canterbury]] for the [[Short Parliament]]. In November 1640, he was re-elected MP for Canterbury in the [[Long Parliament]] and remained until 1653, surviving [[Pride's Purge]].<ref>{{Cite Notitia Parliamentaria|converted=1|part=2|pages=229\u2013239}}</ref> He was elected MP for Canterbury in 1661 and sat until 1679 in the [[Cavalier Parliament]].<ref>{{Rayment-hc|c|2|date=March 2012}}</ref> He was knighted in 1660.\n\nMaster(s) died aged 80 and was buried with a memorial at St Paul's Church, Canterbury.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jy0tAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA275&lpg=PA275&dq=%22Sir+Edward+Master%22+Canterbury&source=bl&ots=SLhbO8LZud&sig=uvQ9kYhFDLX_MiHgjnhuTNZHNkA&hl=en&ei=iBjkTIe3GYeDhQfTlcXODg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CEEQ6AEwBzgU#v=onepage&q=%22Sir%20Edward%20Master%22%20Canterbury&f=false Edward Hasted ''The History and topographical survey of the county of Kent, Volume 11'']</ref> He had married in 1635, Dorcas, the daughter of Sir [[Hugh Hamersley]], Lord Mayor of London 1627-8, and had many children, including at least 4 sons.<ref name=HoP/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|en}}\n{{succession box \n| title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Canterbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Canterbury]] \n| before= ''Parliament suspended since 1629''\n| with= [[John Nutt (MP)|John Nutt]]\n| years=1640\u20131653\n| after= ''Not represented in Barebones parliament''\n}}\n{{succession box\n|before=[[Anthony Aucher]]\n| before2=[[Heneage Finch, 1st Earl of Nottingham|Heneage Finch]]\n|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Canterbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Canterbury]]\n|with=[[Francis Lovelace (MP)|Francis Lovelace]] (1661\u20131664)\n|with2=[[Thomas Hardres]] (1664\u20131679)\n|years=1661\u20131679\n|after=[[Sir Edward Hales, 3rd Baronet|Edward Hales]]\n| after2=[[William Jacob (Canterbury MP)|William Jacob]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Master, Edward}}\n[[Category:1610 births]]\n[[Category:1691 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kent]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Kent]]\n[[Category:Politics of Canterbury]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1640 (April)]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1640\u20131648]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1648\u20131653]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1661\u20131679]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n\n\n{{England-pre1707-MP-stub}}\n{{England-mayor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1627-8 \u2192 1627\u20138", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Master"}
{"title_page": "William Martyn (Lord Mayor)", "text_new": "{{Cleanup|reason=This genealogy chart is very hard to read in its current form|date=September 2011}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n'''Sir William Martin''' of [[Athelhampton]], near [[Dorchester, Dorset]] (c. 1446 &ndash; 14 January 1503) was [[Sheriff of London]] in 1484 and [[Lord Mayor of London]] in 1492. He built the current Great Hall of [[Athelhampton]] in or around 1485. He also received licence to enclose 160 acres (647,000 m\u00b2) of deer park and [[licence to fortify]] his manor. \n\nEffigies of him and his family can be seen in the Church of Saint Mary in nearby [[Puddletown]].\n\n==Genealogy: Martyn of Athelhampton==\n\n    Sir Robert Martin of Waterston, 2nd son of Sir Nicholas [[FitzMartin]]\n   =Amy\n    |\n  |_____________________________________________________________________\n    |                                     |                        |\n    |                                     |                        |\n    Nicholas of Waterston, d. Dec. 1326.  Edmund of Withycomb  Sir Robert of Yeovilton, d.1355.\n   =Margery, fl. 1319.\n    |\n    |________________________________________________\n    |                                               |\n    |                                               |\n    Sir Robert of Waterston, c. 1301-Sept. 1375.    Joan\n   =Agnes de Loundres                              =John Gouytz/Govis\n    |\n    |______________________________________________________\n    |             |                      |\n    |             |                      |\n    Robert        Richard, fl. 1389.     William, dead by 1428\n  d.s.p.&nbsp;1405.   =Elizabeth             =Johanna, alive 1428.\n                  |\n    ______________|______________\n   |                            |\n   |                            |\n   John of Athelhampton         Thomas of Athelhampton, d. 14th Sept. 1485.\n     alive 1431                =dau. of Sir John Clevedon\n             