named-ambassador-to-Japan|archivedate=23 November 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Japan-Australia relations]]\n*[[Foreign relations of Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|Ambassadors of Australia to Japan}}\n*[http://australia.or.jp/en/ Australian Embassy, Tokyo]\n\n{{Lists of heads of Australian diplomatic missions}}\n\n[[Category:Australia\u2013Japan relations]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Australia to Japan| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of ambassadors of Australia|Japan]]\n[[Category:Lists of ambassadors to Japan|Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "miscapitalization (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_ambassadors_of_Australia_to_Japan"}
{"title_page": "Cecil Manning", "text_new": "[[File:Cecil Aubrey Gwynne Manning.jpg|alt=Portrait of Cecil Aubrey Gwyne Manning (23 May 1892 \u2013 12 April 1985) taken circa 1945|thumb|Cecil Aubrey Gwynne Manning (23 May 1892 \u2013 12 April 1985)]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n'''Cecil Aubrey Gwynne Manning''' (23 May 1892 \u2013 12 April 1985) was a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician.<ref name=whowho>{{cite web|title=MANNING, Cecil Aubrey Gwynne|work=[[Who Was Who]]|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date=December 2007|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U166794|accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nHaving fought with the [[London Regiment]] in France in the [[First World War]], Manning was wounded and lost his right arm.\n\nAfter the war he entered local government in London: he was a member of [[Metropolitan Borough of Wandsworth|Wandsworth Borough Council]] from 1919\u20131922, and was elected to the [[London County Council]] in 1922, representing [[Camberwell North (London County Council constituency)|Camberwell North]], serving as leader of the opposition in 1929-30 and deputy chairman from 1930\u201331. He retired from the county council in 1932, having been elected a member of [[Metropolitan Borough of Camberwell|Camberwell Borough Council]] in the previous year. He remained a member of the borough council until 1953, and was Mayor of Camberwell for the final two years of his membership. In 1937 he returned to the county council, remaining a member until 1950, representing Camberwell North again, and then [[Peckham (London County Council constituency)|Peckham]] for the final year.<ref name=whowho/>\n\nDuring the [[Second World War]] he took an active part in the defence of the capital in the [[Air Raid Precautions|ARP]] and Civil Defence organisations, and was Invasion Defence Controller for Camberwell in 1939\u201344.<ref name=whowho/>\n\nIn 1944 he was elected to the [[United Kingdom House of Commons|House of Commons]] at a by-election as [[member of parliament]] for [[Camberwell North (UK Parliament constituency)|Camberwell North]]. He held the seat until 1950.<ref name=whowho/>\n\nHe moved to [[Somerset]], where he was a member [[Shepton Mallet]] Urban District Council from 1954\u201368, serving as chairman in 1967\u201368.<ref name=whowho/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{Rayment-hc|c|1|date=March 2012}}\n* ''The Times'', 1 April 1944\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-cecil-manning | Cecil Manning }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Charles Ammon, 1st Baron Ammon|Charles Ammon]] }}\n{{s-ttl \n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Camberwell North (UK Parliament constituency)|Camberwell North]]\n  | years  = [[1944 Camberwell North by-election|1944]] \u2013 [[1950 United Kingdom general election|1950]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason  = constituency abolished }}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=Leader of the Labour Party on [[London County Council]]|years=1929\u20131930|before=[[Herbert Morrison]]|after=[[Lewis Silkin]]}}\n{{s-civic}}\n{{succession box|title=Mayor of Camberwell|years=1951\u20131953|before=[[Charles Ammon, 1st Baron Ammon|Charles Ammon]]|after=Rosina Whyatt}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manning, Cecil}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of London County Council]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1935\u20131945]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1945\u20131950]]\n[[Category:British politicians with physical disabilities]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Greater London]]\n[[Category:English amputees]]\n[[Category:Members of Camberwell Metropolitan Borough Council]]\n\n\n{{England-Labour-UK-MP-stub}}\n{{England-mayor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Cecil Aubrey Gwynne Manning.jpg|alt=Portrait of Cecil Aubrey Gwyne Manning (23 May 1892 \u2013 12 April 1985) taken circa 1945|thumb|Cecil Aubrey Gwynne Manning (23 May 1892 \u2013 12 April 1985)]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n'''Cecil Aubrey Gwynne Manning''' (23 May 1892 \u2013 12 April 1985) was a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician.<ref name=whowho>{{cite web|title=MANNING, Cecil Aubrey Gwynne|work=[[Who Was Who]]|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date=December 2007|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U166794|accessdate=7 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nHaving fought with the [[London Regiment]] in France in the [[First World War]], Manning was wounded and lost his right arm.\n\nAfter the war he entered local government in London: he was a member of [[Metropolitan Borough of Wandsworth|Wandsworth Borough Council]] from 1919-1922, and was elected to the [[London County Council]] in 1922, representing [[Camberwell North (London County Council constituency)|Camberwell North]], serving as leader of the opposition in 1929-30 and deputy chairman from 1930-31. He retired from the county council in 1932, having been elected a member of [[Metropolitan Borough of Camberwell|Camberwell Borough Council]] in the previous year. He remained a member of the borough council until 1953, and was Mayor of Camberwell for the final two years of his membership. In 1937 he returned to the county council, remaining a member until 1950, representing Camberwell North again, and then [[Peckham (London County Council constituency)|Peckham]] for the final year.<ref name=whowho/>\n\nDuring the [[Second World War]] he took an active part in the defence of the capital in the [[Air Raid Precautions|ARP]] and Civil Defence organisations, and was Invasion Defence Controller for Camberwell in 1939\u201344.<ref name=whowho/>\n\nIn 1944 he was elected to the [[United Kingdom House of Commons|House of Commons]] at a by-election as [[member of parliament]] for [[Camberwell North (UK Parliament constituency)|Camberwell North]]. He held the seat until 1950.<ref name=whowho/>\n\nHe moved to [[Somerset]], where he was a member [[Shepton Mallet]] Urban District Council from 1954\u201368, serving as chairman in 1967-68.<ref name=whowho/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{Rayment-hc|c|1|date=March 2012}}\n* ''The Times'', 1 April 1944\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-cecil-manning | Cecil Manning }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Charles Ammon, 1st Baron Ammon|Charles Ammon]] }}\n{{s-ttl \n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Camberwell North (UK Parliament constituency)|Camberwell North]]\n  | years  = [[1944 Camberwell North by-election|1944]] \u2013 [[1950 United Kingdom general election|1950]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason  = constituency abolished }}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=Leader of the Labour Party on [[London County Council]]|years=1929\u20131930|before=[[Herbert Morrison]]|after=[[Lewis Silkin]]}}\n{{s-civic}}\n{{succession box|title=Mayor of Camberwell|years=1951\u20131953|before=[[Charles Ammon, 1st Baron Ammon|Charles Ammon]]|after=Rosina Whyatt}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manning, Cecil}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of London County Council]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1935\u20131945]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1945\u20131950]]\n[[Category:British politicians with physical disabilities]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Greater London]]\n[[Category:English amputees]]\n[[Category:Members of Camberwell Metropolitan Borough Council]]\n\n\n{{England-Labour-UK-MP-stub}}\n{{England-mayor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1919-1922 \u2192 1919\u20131922 (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cecil_Manning"}
{"title_page": "Wilson Lloyd", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n'''Wilson Lloyd''' (3 September 1835&nbsp;\u2013 4 September 1908)<ref>{{rayment-hc|w|2|date=March 2012}}</ref> was an English [[iron founder]] and a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician who twice sat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] between 1885 and 1895.\n\nLloyd was the son of Samuel Lloyd (1795-1862), known as \"[[Quaker]] Lloyd\", and his wife Mary Honychurch. His father had developed the Old Park Ironworks at [[Wednesbury]] and by the mid-19th century, Messrs. Lloyds Foster and Co. was the town's leading ironworks, employing 1200 men. The family sold the Ironworks in 1867,<ref name=\"quaker-lloyd\">[http://www.blackcountrybugle.co.uk/blackcountrybugle-news/displayarticle.asp?id=74898 Black Country Bugle ''Quaker Lloyd'' 4 May 2006]</ref>\n\nLloyd became a [[Justice of the Peace|J.P.]] and an Alderman. He was elected as the [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Wednesbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Wednesbury]] at the [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885 general election]],<ref>{{London Gazette\n |issue= 25541\n |date=18 December 1885\n |page=6138\n |city=London\n }}</ref> but lost the seat in the [[1886 United Kingdom general election|1886 election]].<ref name=\"craig1885-1918\">{{cite book\n |last=Craig\n |first=F. W. S.\n |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig\n |title=British parliamentary election results 1885\u20131918\n |origyear=1974\n |edition= 2nd\n |year=1989\n |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services\n |location=Chichester\n |isbn= 0-900178-27-2\n |page=204\n}}</ref> He was Wednesbury's second Mayor from 1888 to 1890.<ref name=\"quaker-lloyd\" /> At the [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892 general election]], he was elected again as MP for Wednesbury,<ref>{{London Gazette\n |issue= 26311\n |date=29 July 1892\n |page=4311\n |city=London\n }}</ref> but he did not stand again at the [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895 general election]].<ref name=\"craig1885-1918\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-wilson-lloyd | Wilson Lloyd }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wednesbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Wednesbury]]\n | years  = [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]]\u2013[[1886 United Kingdom general election|1886]]\n | before = [[Alexander Brogden]]\n | after  = [[Philip Stanhope, 1st Baron Weardale|Philip Stanhope]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wednesbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Wednesbury]]\n | years  = [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]]\u2013[[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895]]\n | before = [[Philip Stanhope, 1st Baron Weardale|Philip Stanhope]]\n | after  = [[Walford Davis Green]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lloyd, Wilson}}\n[[Category:1835 births]]\n[[Category:1908 deaths]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1892\u20131895]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in the West Midlands (county)]]\n[[Category:Politics of Sandwell]]\n[[Category:People from Wednesbury]]\n\n\n{{Conservative-UK-MP-1830s-stub}}\n{{England-mayor-stub}}\n{{England-Conservative-UK-MP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n'''Wilson Lloyd''' (3 September 1835&nbsp;\u2013 4 September 1908)<ref>{{rayment-hc|w|2|date=March 2012}}</ref> was an English [[iron founder]] and a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician who twice sat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] between 1885 and 1895.\n\nLloyd was the son of Samuel Lloyd (1795-1862), known as \"[[Quaker]] Lloyd\", and his wife Mary Honychurch. His father had developed the Old Park Ironworks at [[Wednesbury]] and by the mid-19th century, Messrs. Lloyds Foster and Co. was the town\u2019s leading ironworks, employing 1200 men. The family sold the Ironworks in 1867,<ref name=\"quaker-lloyd\">[http://www.blackcountrybugle.co.uk/blackcountrybugle-news/displayarticle.asp?id=74898 Black Country Bugle ''Quaker Lloyd'' 4 May 2006]</ref>\n\nLloyd became a [[Justice of the Peace|J.P.]] and an Alderman. He was elected as the [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Wednesbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Wednesbury]] at the [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885 general election]],<ref>{{London Gazette\n |issue= 25541\n |date=18 December 1885\n |page=6138\n |city=London\n }}</ref> but lost the seat in the [[1886 United Kingdom general election|1886 election]].<ref name=\"craig1885-1918\">{{cite book\n |last=Craig\n |first=F. W. S.\n |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig\n |title=British parliamentary election results 1885\u20131918\n |origyear=1974\n |edition= 2nd\n |year=1989\n |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services\n |location=Chichester\n |isbn= 0-900178-27-2\n |page=204\n}}</ref> He was Wednesbury\u2019s second Mayor from 1888 to 1890.<ref name=\"quaker-lloyd\" /> At the [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892 general election]], he was elected again as MP for Wednesbury,<ref>{{London Gazette\n |issue= 26311\n |date=29 July 1892\n |page=4311\n |city=London\n }}</ref> but he did not stand again at the [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895 general election]].<ref name=\"craig1885-1918\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-wilson-lloyd | Wilson Lloyd }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wednesbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Wednesbury]]\n | years  = [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]]\u2013[[1886 United Kingdom general election|1886]]\n | before = [[Alexander Brogden]]\n | after  = [[Philip Stanhope, 1st Baron Weardale|Philip Stanhope]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]